			<div class="blogComment">
				<a name="108700838009132789"></a> 
				This is Robby, decided not to bother with yet another login to remember.  Here's my two cents, delievered with my usual reagard for punctuality.<br /><br />Have you already ordered your new fruit?  On your decision to migrate...what exactly are you migrating from?  Microsoft software?  The x86 architecture?  Open platfrom computing?  I'm by no means shooting down your decision, I'm just interested to know the reasoning behind it.  When I became lusty for Mac-dom, I quit just before buying time after deeper consideration (though, as you know, that could apply to any of my decisions).  I didn't buy a Mac because I didn't want to: pay the price premium, buy a proprietary machine, or buy into a commercial UNIX.  You can still run Linux on the box (check out the Gentoo-PPC64 project) though.<br /><br />Whereas you know me mostly as a Linux enthusiast, my first love is hardware.  I sincerely recommend you do not buy a new Mac unless it's based on a PCI Express expansion bus architecture.  From what I've seen thus far, Apple is going with PCI-X (aka PCI Extended) for their new expansion bus.  This is only a stop-gap solution, I strongly suggest not putting money into it unless you're building a server.  I have just two more bits, I'm sure you're already tired of hearing this.  <br /><br />First off, don't be impressed by the high FSB clock speed.  The Front Side Bus is defined as the bus between the CPU and the Northbrige controller chip (specifically the memory controller).  The G5 has a built-in memory controller, and thus has no FSB at all by the traditional definition.  The FSB of a G5 will always be half of its clock speed (in this case, 1.25GHz) because that rating is actually the rating of its internal concurrent HyperTransport bus.  If you remember back in the days when a CPU's L2 cache was half-speed relative to the host processor, the calculations work roughly that way.<br /><br />Secondly, be extremely wary of any new large displays from Apple.  Chances are, the statistics of "dead pixel" formation will be even less in your favor.  Your best bet is to go for the smallest display in the new series, as it will have all the design improvements necessary to minimize dead pixels on the large displays without putting near the stress on the implementation.<br /><br />As ever, I hope all goes well.<br />
				<div class="byline"><a href="http://www.devlogik.com/www/E3R_2/blog/2004/06/thank-gawd-for-student-discounts.php#108700838009132789" title="permanent link">#</a> posted by Anonymous @ 10:46 PM</div>
