			<div class="blogComment">
				<a name="108727636508920608"></a> 
				Hello,<br /><br />we don't know each other, but i happened to run by your enthusiasm for Macs. Pardon the intrusion, but i would like to set a couple of points straight:<br /><br />1) PPC processors have never been, and never will be, faster than the x86 standard. The only processor that the G series can be faster than would be a VIA chip. PPC instructins are not meant to handle large bytes of code, nor is it meant to do bit calculations (much like the ones needed to run an OS or Office Software).<br />Since you are a design major, i can see that you are falling for "mac's are best for graphics work" argument. This is sheer wishful thinking. Of all the processors, AMD is, by far the most graphic capable chip. A few simple whetstone/drystone tests, and some photoshop filter timings will prove this quite handily. AMD wins in all but two filters (not the complicated ones either). PPC beats it by a very slim margin in both. Secondly, 99% of all graphic apps cannot make use of two processors, so why have them?<br /><br /><br />2)You are correct, Mac screens, generally speaking are the best. However, i can name a Sony that gets even higher marks, and will save you $1000 or so.<br /><br />3)FSB does not exist when there is an onboard memory controller. Period. "Virtual FSB" is pure marketing langauge. Only a fool would try to imitate/facilitate hardware level communication with an OS. Also, FSB has little to do with actual CPU utilization. Threads are controlled by the OS, and queues are handled seperatly from the core.<br /><br />4)the video cards/sound cards in Macs are not the same as in PC's. The coding is entirley different. Performance levels are different as well. Nor will an extra 128MB of vram yeild any decent performance boost. Also, gamers cards are not meant for graphics work; they misplace pixels. If you want a performance increase, you need to be looking at Qurado 4's, Fire GL's, Matrox, or Wildcat.<br /><br />5)Mac's may be prettier than PC's but they have recently had major design flaws, causing board failures, and terrible case stress. Apple refused to fix or even acknowledge the problem until a year later, after a mass demonstartion was held. Besides, there are plenty of PC's that imitate Apple's beauty.<br /><br />6) OSX is not UNIX. Darwin is based on BSD, which is derived from UNIX. Futhermore, you will never see it, as Aqua has nothing at all to do with the base OS. While intuitive, all of its features, design quirks, and eye candy, can be easily reproduced by Linux or even Windows XP. <br /><br />7) Mac hardware is nowhere near the level of excellence that PC hardware is. You speak of value; Mac cannot retain value becuase of software advances. A well designed PC will outlast and outperform a Mac 100% of the time. Not to mention the upgradeability. ALso note, that apple uses Class B ram, and Class C boards, same as every other retail. How's that for "well built"?<br /><br />8)100% of Mac software runs in Windows/Linux, or has an exact equivalent. <br /><br />In short, there is entirely no reason to buy a Mac. Its a tremendous amount of money, in return for pretty, long lasting hardware; a rock solid OS, with pretty eye candy, yet is ultimatly useless or entirley outmoded.<br />
				<div class="byline"><a href="http://www.devlogik.com/www/E3R_2/blog/2004/06/thank-gawd-for-student-discounts.php#108727636508920608" title="permanent link">#</a> posted by Anonymous @ 1:12 AM</div>
